WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:07.400
Hi everyone, I am Karan Girthani, I am on the Shiny team and in today's video, we look

00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:14.520
at how to use responsiveness to have a different layout for different screen sizes.

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:19.719
So if you are using a desktop, you can decide to have a different layout of your Shiny app

00:00:19.719 --> 00:00:23.080
as compared to something that's on a much smaller screen like a smartphone.

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:28.000
So for that, what we will do is, most people when they end up creating their Shiny app

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.160
for the first time, they won't end up using columns or anything.

00:00:32.160 --> 00:00:37.639
So they'll just end up creating the UI elements or using the UI elements with the plots.

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:42.320
So in this case, you can see this is a basic layout wherein in Shiny, if you do not give

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:45.680
it, it will actually stretch to the whole full resolution of the screen.

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:51.200
So it is responsive by default, but it will end up taking the whole screen.

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:57.200
So in this case, when if you see how I have a UI card and I have a plot inside it, even

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:01.560
if I stretch it to something that's like much more desktop, it will end up taking the

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:05.639
most of the screen, depending on if it's fluid or fillable or whatever.

00:01:05.639 --> 00:01:11.440
But let's say if I wanted to have like multiple cards on each of them for desktop, but like

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:16.879
for mobile, make sure it's like the same thing, one card because there's not enough room.

00:01:16.879 --> 00:01:22.760
What we will do in this case is we will end up using UI layout columns.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:32.000
So in this case, let's see if I can turn this on, let me collapse this, take this out

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:41.239
and let me put this down, let me format this, okay, cool, all right.

00:01:41.239 --> 00:01:46.480
So in this case, what we do is we use the width UI layout columns.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:52.480
This code is in express mode, but same thing can be done in core as well.

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:56.519
So you see how we are using the column widths and you can see different screen sizes.

00:01:56.519 --> 00:02:02.519
We see the large, medium, small, extra small and large typically is with something that's

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:08.919
like much more desktop, like much higher resolution, more than 900 pixels with medium is more for

00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:15.320
like tablets and small is more smartphones and extra small is like much smaller smartphones.

00:02:15.639 --> 00:02:25.240
So in this case, when you actually stretch it to a desktop, so yeah, so you can see in

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:30.759
a desktop and there's a lot of width, how you can actually see two cards instead of

00:02:30.759 --> 00:02:37.199
just one and then you can decide if you want the same configuration for the other cards

00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:39.960
as well, or you can have it take the whole screen.

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:46.960
So if you look at how I use my code, I say that like we use the 12 units of measurement

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:50.520
like across the screen, like a bootstrap thing that Shiny uses.

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:56.399
And so I say like the first card should use like six of 12, which is like half and the

00:02:56.399 --> 00:02:59.479
other one should be six, which is the other half.

00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:03.039
And then the third one is 12, which means it ends up using the whole thing.

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:07.800
So when you look at this one, you see how it's using half, half and then the third one

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.600
ends up using the whole thing.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:16.199
But when we go to tablet or smartphone screen sizes, we end up actually using the whole.

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:20.839
So that's why when I shrink it, you end up seeing it occupying the whole width of the

00:03:20.839 --> 00:03:21.839
screen.

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:26.800
If you are interested in learning more about how to use layout columns to make sure your

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:30.679
app is responsive for different screen sizes or having the different configuration for

00:03:30.679 --> 00:03:36.880
your different screen sizes, you can check out our UI.LayoutColumns documentation in

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:40.240
the function reference for either core or express mode.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:45.839
And you can see how they have mentioned how we can use different screen sizes for configuring

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:48.639
how your app looks for these different screen sizes.

00:03:48.639 --> 00:03:49.960
So thank you for watching.

